// Grounded faithfulness suite for the RAG tutor. Mirrors web/lib/tutor/index.ts:
// the model is given ONLY lesson excerpts and must answer from them or abstain.
// Run with a temp models.json whose default_system = the real tutor SYSTEM_PROMPT
// (which already ends in /no_think), so these cases inherit it (no per-task system).
// Categories: grounded (in-context, answerable) | grounded-adversarial (answer NOT
// in the excerpts -> correct behavior is to abstain; regex scores abstain=1, halluc=0).
//
// --- in-context: What is a candlestick? ---
{"id": "g_wick_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: What does a long upper wick on a candle tell you?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (What is a candlestick?) The thin lines above and below the body are the wicks (or shadows); they reach out to the high and the low. A long wick means price went there but didn't stay.", "score": {"type": "any", "any": ["didn't stay", "did not stay", "snapped back", "reached", "went there", "rejection", "but didn't"]}}
{"id": "g_green_open_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: On a green candle, where is the open price?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (What is a candlestick?) For a green candle the open is the bottom of the body and the close is the top. For a red candle it flips: open on top, close on the bottom.", "score": {"type": "any", "any": ["bottom"]}}
{"id": "g_fourprices_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: How many prices does a single candlestick encode, and which are they?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (What is a candlestick?) Each candle squeezes four prices from its slice of time into one shape: the open, high, low, and close.", "score": {"type": "keywords", "all": ["open", "high", "low", "close"]}}
{"id": "g_red_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: What does a red candle tell you?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (What is a candlestick?) Red (or black): the close is below the open - price fell over the period.", "score": {"type": "any", "any": ["fell", "below the open", "down", "decline", "dropped"]}}
{"id": "g_body_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: What does the body of a candle span?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (What is a candlestick?) The thick body spans from the open to the close. The thin wicks reach out to the high and the low.", "score": {"type": "keywords", "all": ["open", "close"]}}
// --- in-context: Line vs candlestick ---
{"id": "g_line_close_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: A line chart usually connects which single price from each period?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (Line charts vs. candlestick charts) A line chart connects one price per period - usually the close - into a single line. It's clean and great for spotting the overall trend at a glance.", "score": {"type": "any", "any": ["close", "closing"]}}
{"id": "g_candle_shows_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: What can a candlestick chart show that a line chart cannot?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (Line charts vs. candlestick charts) A candlestick shows four prices per period instead of one: you can see not just where price ended, but how far it traveled (the range), whether buyers or sellers won (open vs close), and rejection (long wicks).", "score": {"type": "any", "any": ["range", "traveled", "open vs close", "rejection", "who won", "wick"]}}
{"id": "g_line_use_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: When is a line chart the better tool?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (Line charts vs. candlestick charts) Use a line for a quick read of the long-term trend, or comparing several assets at once. Use candles when making an actual trading decision, where the intra-period action matters.", "score": {"type": "any", "any": ["trend", "compar", "several assets", "long-term", "glance"]}}
// --- in-context: Bid, ask, and the spread ---
{"id": "g_buy_pays_ask_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: If I place a market buy order right now, which price do I pay?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (Bid, ask, and the spread) If you buy now (a market order), you pay the ask. If you sell now, you receive the bid. So buying and immediately selling loses you the spread.", "score": {"type": "any", "any": ["ask"]}}
{"id": "g_bid_def_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: What is the bid?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (Bid, ask, and the spread) The bid is the highest price a buyer is currently willing to pay. The ask is the lowest price a seller is willing to accept.", "score": {"type": "any", "any": ["buyer", "willing to pay", "highest price a buyer"]}}
{"id": "g_spread_cost_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: The bid is $10.00 and the ask is $10.05. I buy 100 shares at the ask and immediately sell at the bid. Ignoring fees, how much did I lose to the spread (in dollars)?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (Bid, ask, and the spread) Example: bid $10.00, ask $10.05. Buy 100 shares at the ask = $1,005. Sell them right back at the bid = $1,000. You lost $5 to the spread, ignoring fees.", "score": {"type": "numeric", "value": 5, "tol": 0}}
{"id": "g_tight_spread_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: What does a tight spread usually signal?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (Bid, ask, and the spread) A tight spread (a cent or two) means lots of buyers and sellers - the asset is liquid and cheap to trade. A wide spread means few participants (illiquid).", "score": {"type": "any", "any": ["liquid", "many buyers", "lots of buyers", "cheap to trade"]}}
{"id": "g_limit_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: How does a limit order help with the spread?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (Bid, ask, and the spread) A limit order lets you set your own price instead of accepting the bid/ask - a way to avoid paying the full spread, at the risk of not getting filled.", "score": {"type": "any", "any": ["set your own price", "set your price", "your own price", "avoid", "not getting filled", "may not fill"]}}
// --- in-context: Profit & loss ---
{"id": "g_unrealized_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: What is unrealized P&L?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (Profit & loss) Unrealized P&L is the gain or loss on a position you still hold. It moves every tick - a paper profit. Realized P&L is the gain or loss locked in once you sell.", "score": {"type": "any", "any": ["still hold", "hold", "paper", "not sold", "haven't sold", "before you sell"]}}
{"id": "g_pnl_calc_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: I buy 10 shares at $50 (cost basis $500) and the price is now $58. What is my unrealized P&L in dollars?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (Profit & loss) For a position you bought (going long): P&L = (current price - cost basis) x shares. Buy 10 shares at $50 (cost basis $500); at $58 your unrealized P&L is (58 - 50) x 10 = $80.", "score": {"type": "numeric", "value": 80, "tol": 0}}
{"id": "g_realized_when_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: When does a gain become realized?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (Profit & loss) Realized P&L is the gain or loss locked in once you sell and close the position. Until then it is unrealized - a paper profit that can still vanish.", "score": {"type": "any", "any": ["sell", "close the position", "closed", "locked in"]}}
{"id": "g_cost_basis_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: What is my cost basis?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (Profit & loss) Cost basis is what you actually paid to acquire a position, including fees.", "score": {"type": "any", "any": ["paid", "fees", "acquire"]}}
// --- in-context: P/E ratio ---
{"id": "g_pe_calc_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: A stock trades at $40 and its EPS is $2. What is its P/E ratio?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (The P/E ratio) P/E = share price / EPS. Roughly: dollars paid per $1 of annual earnings.", "score": {"type": "numeric", "value": 20, "tol": 0}}
{"id": "g_pe_high_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: What does a high P/E generally suggest about a company?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (The P/E ratio) A high P/E says the market expects growth; a low P/E says it expects little - or sees risk.", "score": {"type": "any", "any": ["growth", "expect"]}}
{"id": "g_pe_formula_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: How is the P/E ratio calculated?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (The P/E ratio) P/E = share price / EPS (earnings per share). Roughly: the dollars you pay per $1 of annual earnings.", "score": {"type": "any", "any": ["eps", "earnings per share", "earnings", "divided by"]}}
{"id": "g_no_pe_in", "category": "grounded", "prompt": "Question: Why might a company have no meaningful P/E ratio?\n\nLesson excerpts:\n[1] (The P/E ratio) No earnings, no P/E: an unprofitable company has negative or undefined EPS, so the ratio breaks.", "score": {"type": "any", "any": ["no earnings", "negative", "undefined", "unprofitable", "loss", "no profit"]}}
